05087nam a22007335i 9780226730288DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020013380  a9780226730288  a(DE-B1597)570906  a(OCoLC)1196255196  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN1271b.R36 2020 4aPN1271b.R36 2021 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.12231 aRamazani, Jahan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetry in a Global Age /cJahan Ramazani. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 figure, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. “Cosmopolitan Sympathies”: Poetry of the First Global War -- t2. The Local Poem in a Global Age -- t3. Poetry and Tourism in a Global Age -- t4. Modernist Inflections, Postcolonial Directions -- t5. Poetry and the Transnational Migration of Form -- t6. Yeats’s Asias: Modernism, Orientalism, Anti-orientalism -- t7. Poetry, the Planet, and the Ecological Thought: Wallace Stevens and Beyond -- t8. Seamus Heaney’s Globe -- t9. Code-Switching, Code-Stitching: A Macaronic Poetics? -- t10. Poetry, (Un)Translatability, and World Literature -- tEpilogue. Lyric Poetry: Intergeneric, Transnational, Translingual? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIdeas, culture, and capital flow across national borders with unprecedented speed, but we tend not to think of poems as taking part in globalization. Jahan Ramazani shows that poetry has much to contribute to understanding literature in an extra-national frame. Indeed, the globality of poetry, he argues, stands to energize the transnational turn in the humanities. Poetry in a Global Age builds on Ramazani’s award-winning A Transnational Poetics, a book that had a catalytic effect on literary studies. Ramazani broadens his lens to discuss modern and contemporary poems not only in relation to world literature, war, and questions of orientalism but also in light of current debates over ecocriticism, translation studies, tourism, and cultural geography. He offers brilliant readings of postcolonial poets like Agha Shahid Ali, Lorna Goodison, and Daljit Nagra, as well as canonical modernists such as W. B. Yeats, Wallace Stevens, T. S. Eliot, and Marianne Moore. Ramazani shows that even when poetry seems locally rooted, its long memory of forms and words, its connections across centuries, continents, and languages, make it a powerful imaginative resource for a global age. This book makes a strong case for poetry in the future development of world literature and global studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aPoetry, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  acosmopolitanism.  aglobal literature.  aglobalization.  alyric.  amodernism.  apoetry.  apostcolonial.  atransnational poetics.  atwentieth-century poetry.  aworld literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106930960 cprintz978022673000440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226730288423Coveruhttps://www